Introducing HTML5

  • HTML is the predominant markup language used to describe content, or data, on the World Wide Web (WWW)
  • HTML5 is the latest iteraOon of that markup language

Introducing HTML5

• includes:

  • new features,
  • improvements to exisOng features,
  • scripOng-based APIs,
  • all valid elements from both HTML4 and XHTML 1.0,
  • redeﬁniOons of exisOng markup elements,
  • new elements that allow web designers to be more expressive in the semanOcs of their markup

Introducing HTML5

• The term “HTML5” has addiOonally been used to refer to a number of other new technologies and APIs. Some of these include:

  • drawing with the <canvas> element, – oﬄine storage,
  • the new <video> and <audio> elements,
  • drag-and-drop funcOonality,
  • Microdata,
  • embedded fonts, – others.

Introducing CSS3

  • CSS is a style language that describes how HTML markup is presented or styled.
  • CSS3 is the latest version of the CSS speciﬁcaOon
  • New features in CSS3 include support for addiOonal selectors, drop shadows, rounded corners, mulOple backgrounds, animaOon, transparency, and much more.

The secOon element

“The secOon element represents a generic secOon of a document or applicaOon. A secOon, in this context, is a themaOc grouping of content, typically with a heading.” WHATWG

SecOon vs Div

More HTML5 SemanOcs

A New PerspecOve on Types of Content

    • Metadata content
    • – data that’s not present on the page itself, but aﬀects the page’s presentaOon or includes other informaOonabout the page. This includes elements l ike Otle ,link , meta , and style .
  • Flow content

– Includes about every element that’s used in the bodyof an HTML document, including elements likeheader, footer , and even p . The only elements excluded are those that have no eﬀect on the document’s ﬂow: script , link , and meta elements in the page’s head, for example.

A New PerspecOve on Types of Content

• SecOoning content

– This is the most interesOng type of content in HTML5. We menOoned “secOon” previously to refer to a block of content that could contain a heading, footer, or aside. In fact, what we were actually referring to was secOoning content. In HTML5, this includes arOcle, aside, nav, and secOon.

A New PerspecOve on Types of Content

    • Heading content
    • – This type of content deﬁnes the header of a given secOon, and includes the various levels of heading (h1, h2, etc.), as well as the new hgroup element.
  • Phrasing content

– This category is roughly the equivalent to what you’re used to thinking of as inline content, it includes elements like em, strong, cite, etc.

A New PerspecOve on Types of Content

    • Embedded content
    • – For elements that are embedded into a page, such as img, object, embed, video, canvas, and others.
  • InteracOve content

– For content with which users can interact. It consists mainly of form elements, as well as links and other elements that are interacOve only when certain agributes are present.

  • The document outline produces an outlinesummary of an HTML document based on how it is marked up.

The Document Outline

• In HTLM5, each element that falls under the category of “secOoning content” creates a new node in the document outline. Heading (h1 –h6 ) elements within a block of secOoning content also create “implied” secOons.

This results in exactly the same document outline: each piece of sectioning content (the article elements in this example) creates a new branch in the document tree, and so can have its own h1 . This way, each section has its own mini document outline.

The Document Outline

• The advantage of the new outlining algorithm is that it allows us to move an enOre secOon to a completely diﬀerent document while preserving the same markup. Beforehand, a post’s Otle on that post’s page might have been an h1, but the same post’s Otle on the home page or a category page lisOng might have been an h2 or h3. Now, you can just keep the same markup, as long as the headings are grouped together in a secOoning content element.

The progress and meter elements

The Ome element

The Ome element

  • The Ome element has been speciﬁcally designed to deal with the problem of humansreading dates and Omes diﬀerently from machines.

The Ome element

The Ome element

The Ome element has some associated rules and guidelines:

  • You should not use Ome to encode unspeciﬁed dates or Omes (for example, “during the ice age” or “last winter” ).

  • The dateOme agribute has to be a valid date string.
  • the Ome element lacks a dateOme agribute, the element’s text content (whatever appears between theopening and closing tags) needs to be a valid date string.

The uses for the Ome element are endless: calendar events,publicaOon dates (for blog posts, videos, press releases, andso forth), historic dates, transacOon records, arOcle or content updates, and much more.

Changes to exisOng features

  • The b element no longer means ‘boldface’ (style should be in CSS) but now means “stylisOcally oﬀset from the normal prose without conveying any extra importance.”
  • The strong element represents “strong importance for its contents.” and nested strong elements are allowed.

Changes to exisOng features

  • The i element no longer means ‘italicized text’ (style should be in CSS) but now means “a span of text in an al ternate voice or mood, or otherwise oﬀset from the normal prose.”
  • The em element sOll refers to text that’s emphasized. For example, two phrases can have the exact same wording, but their meanings change because of the diﬀerent use of em :

Changes to exisOng features

  • Neither i nor em should be used to mark up a publicaOon Otle; instead, use cite.
  • The big element used to display text in large font is now obsolete and should not be used.
  • The small element used to display text in small font now means “side comments such as small print.”. Some examples where small might be used include informaOon in footer text, ﬁne print,and terms and condiOons.
  • The small element should only be used for short runs of text.

Changes to exisOng features

  • The cite element no longer means “a citaOon or a reference to other sources” and now should be used for “the Otle of a work”.
  • The exisOng dl (deﬁniOon list) element, along with its associated dt (term) and dd (descripOon) children, hasbeen redeﬁned in the HTML5 spec. Previously, in addiOonto terms and deﬁniOons, the spec allowed the dl element to mark up dialogue, but the spec now prohibits this.
  • HTML5, these lists are no longer called “deﬁniOon lists” ;they’re now the more generic-sounding “descripOon lists.” They should be used to mark up any kind of name-valuepairs, including terms and deﬁniOons, metadata topics and values, and quesOons and answers.

Other new elements and features: The details element

Other new elements and features: Customized Ordered Lists

  • HTML5 introduces a new Boolean agribute called reversed that, when present, reverses the order of the ordered list items and has brought back the start agribute, deprecated in HTML4. The start agribute lets you specify with which number your list should begin.
  • Support is good for start , but reversed has yet to be implemented in most browsers.
